{"action":"opened","issue":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/52452","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/52452/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/52452/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/52452/events","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/issues/52452","id":2032389619,"node_id":"I_kwDOABkWpM55I83z","number":52452,"title":"Export `jl_write_coverage_data` or its equivalent in Julia 1.10+","user":{"login":"Drvi","id":2074313,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjIwNzQzMTM=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/2074313?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi","html_url":"https://github.com/Drvi","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Drvi/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"open","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":0,"created_at":"2023-12-08T10:25:35Z","updated_at":"2023-12-08T10:25:35Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"NONE","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"Since https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/49600 `jl_write_coverage_data` is no longer exported, making it inaccessible in Julia 1.10+. We recently started calling it (as `ccall(:jl_write_coverage_data, Cvoid, (Ptr{Cvoid},), Base.JLOptions().output_code_coverage)`) in our tests since we're using [ReTestItems.jl](https://github.com/JuliaTesting/ReTestItems.jl) which runs tests in multiple Julia processes in a parallel. Sometimes one of the test-running processes dies (e.g. we kill a worker on timeout or when the machine is getting too close to OOMing), at which point we lose the coverage information from it -- and our mitigation for that is calling `jl_write_coverage_data` after each test item. This seems to work well on 1.9 but is not currently compatible with 1.10 and onwards.

It would be great to have the option to generate coverage files eagerly on 1.10.

